{This course is a repertoire for Black based on the Queen's Gambit. It can be
played against all White's main moves except 1.e4.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {
There are four ways for Black to play the Queen's Gambit: 3...Nf6; 3...Be7; 3..
.a6; 3...h6. All of these moves are similar and can sometimes even transpose
into each other. The choice in this course is the move 3...h6.} h6 {This is an
old move which has recently become popular. It's a very good and reliable
system that has some theory, but it's more important to study it on
understanding since knowing how to play the arising positions is more
important than concrete knowledge. In addition, this move also works against
the 3.Nf3 move order. With 3...h6, Black prevents White from playing Bg5 after
Black plays ...Nf6, which would pin the knight. Sooner or later, White will
capture on d5, so cxd5 and exd5 will be played. Because of that, it's
important to study the arising pawn structure and the minority attack.} 4. Nf3
Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {Activating the bishop before playing the move e2-e3.}
(6. e3 Bd6 {The position can turn out to be a reversed Torre if ...Bg4, or a
reversed London if ...Bf5.} 7. Be2 c6 8. O-O O-O {Black has a very good
version of the Carlsbad structure due to the strong bishop on d6 and the
potential attack on White's king, so the position is already much better for
Black.} 9. a3 {[%csl Rc1,Rd4,Re3,Rf2] There's no minority attack when White's
dark-squared bishop is blocked within the pawn chain on c1. In order for White
to carry out a successful minority attack, the c1-bishop has to be active on
the f4-square or exchanged. In conclusion, the minority attack for White would
be a waste of time and Black will have a very strong attack against White's
king.}) 6... Bd6 {6...c6 is less flexible, so it's better to start with 6...
Bd6.} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 c6 9. Rc1 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. O-O Nbd7
13. Rfd1 Qe7 {The position is around equal, but practically, Black may be
already better.} 14. a3 Ne4 {The knight is heading to the d6-square. The
knight can also reach it via e8, but with Ne4, it gives Black more
possibilities and White can't capture it with Nxe4 due to the dxe4 fork.} 15.
Nd2 Nxd2 {A much better move than Nd6.} (15... Nd6 {The ideal scenario for
Black would be to have only one minor piece - the knight on d6, against one
minor piece of White's, for example a light-squared bishop or a knight. So as
a rule: the more minor pieces White keeps, it's better for White.}) 16. Qxd2
Nb6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb6c4,Gc4d6,Gb6c8,Gc8d6] The knight is heading towards
the d6-square, with the goal to reach the ideal set-up for Black.} *

