{[%evp 0,36,38,30,22,4,4,4,-12,2,24,11,23,10,10,8,10,11,23,26,23,10,0,-10,-5,
-5,46,11,14,-28,13,9,8,-5,-7,-21,-16,-11,-12]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4.
Nc3 h6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 (8. g3 $2 {This move in the
Carlsbad pawn structure is strategically wrong. With g3 and Bg2, White's
light-squared bishop is very bad since it's hitting in a wall of pawns - the
structure d5-c6-b7. The bishop is not targeting Black's king and in addition,
if White ever plays b4, the c4-square will be very weak since the bishop is
not protecting it.} c6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Bf5 11. Rc1 Nbd7 12. e3 Ne4 (12...
Qe7 {Is also possible.}) 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. a3 Nb6 (14... Bxf3 {Black can also
trade on f3 and then reroute the knight to the d6-square.}) 15. Re1 Qe7 16. Qe2
Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nc8 (17... f5 {Is also possible, with the idea to prevent any
search for counterplay with e3-e4 from White.}) 18. Qc2 Nd6 19. b4 Rac8 20. Be2
a6 21. Qb3 Qe6 22. a4 b5 {Black plays b5! only when White threates to play
b4-b5.} 23. axb5 axb5 24. Ra1 g6 (24... Nc4 {Is also possible.}) 25. Ra7 h5 $11
{Black is simply improving the position on the kingside. The move Nc4 is
possible at any time.}) 8... O-O (8... Bf5 {Black would like to develop the
bishop, but White has:} 9. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7] Putting pressure on the b7-pawn.})
9. Rc1 (9. Bd3 Bg4 10. h3 (10. O-O c6) (10. Qb3 {The position may be playable
for Black, but there is no need to enter it.} Bxf3 $5 (10... Nc6 $5) 11. gxf3 (
11. Qxb7 $4 Bxg2 $19 12. Rg1) 11... Nbd7 12. O-O-O c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qc2 a6
15. Kb1 Rac8 16. Qd2 $11 b5 17. Ne2 Nfd7 18. Nd4 Ne5 $15) 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 (
11. Qxf3 Nbd7 (11... c6 $6 12. g4 $36) 12. g4 c5 {A flank attack is punished
by a strike in the center!}) 11... c5 12. Nb5 Qe7 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd4 Nc6 15.
Nxc6 Qxc6 $15 {White's king is feeling uncomfortable as there's nowhere to
hide properly.} (15... bxc6 $15)) (9. Qc2 {This is a good move since it
prevents Black's light-squared bishop to be activated. Bf5 is not possible
anymore, and on Bg4, White has Ne5.} c6 $1 (9... Nc6 $5 {This is an
interesting possibility that Black can try against Qc2. Black is threatening
to play Nb4 and it's controlling the e5-square.} 10. Be2 (10. a3 Bg4 11. Nd2
Rfe8 12. Nb3 a6 13. Bd3 Ne7 14. O-O Bh5 15. Nc5 Rab8 16. b4 c6 17. a4 Bg6 18.
Bxg6 Nxg6 19. b5 axb5 20. axb5 b6 21. Nd3 c5 $11) 10... Bg4 {Black is going to
trade a minor piece successfully.} 11. O-O a6 12. Rac1 Ne7 (12... Na7 {Is an
interesting possibility, with the idea to reroute the knight to d6 via the c8
or b5-square later on.}) (12... Nd8 {Is possible, although from this square,
the knight is not really heading to d6.} 13. a3 {White is trying to play b4.} (
13. Na4 c6 14. Nc5 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qe7 16. Rfe1 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. Be2 Ne4 19.
Bd3 Nd6 20. b4 Rac8 21. a4 g6 {Black is simply improving the position, as 22.
b5 is not possible at the moment due to 22...cxb5 with tempo.} (21... f5 {
Is another possible move.}) 22. Qb3 {Now White might be threatening b5, so
Black plays:} b5 23. axb5 axb5 24. Ra1 Nc4 25. Ra7 Ra8 {Black is the one
fighting for an advantage.} 26. Rea1 $2 Rxa7 27. Rxa7 Nxe3 $1 $19 {Black has
this tactic in this concrete position, although if it was slightly different
and it wasn't possible, Kg7 would simply improve the position and it would be
Black who is taking over.}) 13... Ne6 14. b4 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 16. Qb2 Ng5 $11)
13. Na4 c6 14. Nc5 Bxf3 (14... Qc7 15. Ne5 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Nf5 17. Ng4 $6 Nxg4
18. Qxg4 Nd6 19. Qd7 Qb8 20. Rfd1 Rd8 21. Qg4 Qc7 22. b3 Qe7 23. Nd3 g6 24. Nf4
Qf6 25. Nh5 Qe7 26. Nf4 Kh7 27. Nd3 Re8 28. Ne5 Rad8 29. h3 h5 30. Qe2 f6 31.
Nf3 Qf7 32. Nd2 h4 33. Qd3 Kg8 34. Nf3 g5 $15) 15. Bxf3 {A typical position
where Black's e7-knight is heading to the d6-square.} Qc7 {Freeing the
d6-square for the knight.} 16. Qb3 Rab8 17. Be2 Nc8 18. Rfd1 Nd6 19. Qc2 Qe7
20. b4 Nd7 21. Nxd7 (21. a4 Nb6) 21... Qxd7 22. a4 Rbc8 23. Qb2 b5 $11) 10. Bd3
{Black can't play Bf5 and 10...Bg4 will be met with 11.Ne5. In this case where
the bishop from c8 can't be actively developed, Black is aiming to occupy the
e4-square!} (10. Be2 {Allows Bg4 which would trade a pair of minor pieces.} Bg4
11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rab1 Nb6 13. Ne5 (13. b4 a6 14. a4 Qe7 15. b5 cxb5 16. axb5 a5
$17) 13... Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nfd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. b3 Nc8 17. Na4 Nd6 18. Nc5 Qe7
19. Nd3 Rfe8 {Black has better prospects in this standard position.}) 10...
Nbd7 11. O-O Re8 12. Rac1 Qe7 {[%csl Ge4]} 13. a3 (13. Nd2 {Preventing ...Ne4.
So now Black needs another plan, which is playing Nb6, Be6, and then rerouting
the b6-knight with Nc8-Nd6.} Nb6 14. Rfe1 Be6 15. Nb3 Nc8 16. Nc5 Nd6 17. Nxe6
Qxe6 18. b4 Rac8 19. Qb3 a6 20. h3 Nd7 21. a4 Nb6 (21... b5 $11) 22. b5 cxb5
23. axb5 a5 {A typical idea to meet the b4-b5 push which will be discussed
later.} 24. Qa3 Ndc4 $11) 13... Ne4 14. b4 (14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2 Nf6 {With
ideas like Bf5, Qd6, and Ng4.}) 14... Ndf6 15. Ne5 (15. Rfe1 Bf5 16. Qb2 Nxc3
17. Rxc3 (17. Bxf5 Nce4 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Ne5 Nd6 20. a4 a6 21. Nd3 g6 $15 {
White doesn't have an active plan and Black will improve the position on the
kingside and at some point, create an attack against White's king.}) 17... Bxd3
18. Rxd3 a6 19. Ne5 Ne4 20. a4 Nd6 $15) 15... Bf5 16. Ne2 {White is retreating
the knight and threatening f3, with the point that Black won't have the move
Nxc3.} (16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. f3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nd7 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Black is already
better as the e3-pawn is weak, and if White pushes e4, Black will trade on e4,
and then White's central pawns e4 and d4 will be targets.} 20. e4 dxe4 21. fxe4
a5 22. Kh1 axb4 23. axb4 Ra2 $15) (16. f3 Nxc3 17. Bxf5 Nb5 18. Qb2 Nd6 19. Bd3
Nd7 20. f4 f6 $17) 16... Bh7 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gf6h7,Gg8h7] The bishop is now
defended, so the knight from e4 is free to move.} 17. Ng3 $2 (17. b5 c5 {
A typical reaction to b4-b5 when there is a White knight on e5, since the pawn
on d4 can't move.}) 17... Nxg3 18. hxg3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Ne4 20. Nf3 (20. b5 c5
21. Nf3 c4 $19) 20... Nd6 {In a standard position like this, White would like
to have a healthy pawn structure in front of the king with the pawns on h2, g2,
and f2. The reason for that is if White has any move like h3, g3, or hxg3 like
in this situation, all of them can serve as a hook which accelerates Black's
attack.} 21. a4 a6 22. Ne5 (22. Rfe1 g6 23. Ne5 Kg7 $17) 22... h5 23. Qe2 g6
24. Qc2 Kg7 25. Rfd1 Rh8 $17) 9... Nc6 (9... c6 10. Be2 {Allows Bg4, trading a
pair of minor pieces.} Bg4 11. Qb3 (11. O-O Nbd7 {WIth a typical position
where the light-squared bishop from g4 will be traded and Black will reroute a
knight to d6 at some point.}) 11... Qe7 12. O-O Ne4 $1 13. Rfd1 Nd6 14. Ne5
Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Nd7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Black managed to get an ideal scenario. A
position with a knight on d6 against a White minor piece is good for Black.
White doesn't have any active plan, and pushing b4-a4-b5 would weaken the
c4-square and Black will play ...b5 only when White is threatening b4-b5!,
which means Nc3 and a4 have to be included in this case.} 17. Nf4 Rfe8 18. Nd3
a6 {This is a good prophylactic move against a potential minority attack from
White. Black can continue to improve the position on the kingside by
transferring a rook to g6, or simply with moves like g6, h5, Kg7, and then
depending on what White does.}) 10. Be2 Bf5 11. O-O a6 12. a3 (12. Nh4 Bh7 (
12... Be6 {Is also possible.} 13. Bd3 Na7 14. Nf5 {Black is not afraid of this
move since the trades are in Black's favor, as the goal is to stay with only
one pair of minor pieces on the board, from which the Black knight would be
ideal on the d6-square.} Bxf5 15. Bxf5 Qe7 16. Re1 Nb5 $1 17. Nxb5 $2 axb5 {
This is a very solid and good pawn structure for Black due to the semi-open
a-file.} 18. a3 c6 19. Bd3 Rfe8 $15) 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Ne7 $11) 12... Na7
13. b4 c6 14. Ne5 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Re1 Nc8 17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nd6 *

