{In the Queen's Gambit, it's far more important to understand the typical
ideas than to learn exact moves, especially in the cxd5 lines where Black
plays ...h6, because the positions are very similar and recognizing where one
idea works and where one doesn't, is more important.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. e3 Bxg3 9. hxg3 Re8 (9...
Qe7 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 Bg4 11. Qb3 c6 12. O-O Ne4 $1 {The knight is heading to
the d6-square. It can also reach d6 via e8, but on e4 is more active and gives
more possibilities. In addition, White can't capture the knight with Nxe4
because after dxe4, White loses a piece.} 13. Rfe1 Nd6 $15) 10... c6 11. O-O
Nbd7 {Bg4 was possible but it's not as good as when White has the pawn back on
h2 instead of g3. The reason is that Bxf3 would repair White's pawn structure
a bit after gxf3.} 12. Qc2 Re8 13. a3 Ne4 14. Rab1 Ndf6 15. b4 Bf5 (15... Ng4
$1 $15) 16. Ne5 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Ne4 $3 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ge4d6]} 19.
Rfc1 (19. b5 $2 c5 $19) 19... Nd6 20. a4 a6 $17 {It's important to note that
g6 can be met with Nxg6, and White would have a perpetual at least since Black
can't cover with Qg7 and defend the knight on d6 at the same time. Instead,
Black can simply prepare g6 with a move like Qe6.}) 10. Bd3 c6 {Playing Bg4 is
not very effective since Bxf3 at any point can be met with gxf3, improving
White's kingside pawn structure.} 11. O-O Qe7 12. Qc2 {Whenever the moves Bg4
and Bf4 aren't possible or they are ineffective, then a good plan is playing
to control the e4-square and jump Ne4 at some point. The moves Nbd7, Qe7, Re8,
Ne4, Ndf6, Bf5! and Nxc3 if needed, should feature in Black's plans.} Nbd7 (
12... Be6 {Is also possible.} 13. Rab1 Nbd7 14. b4 Rac8 15. a4 g6 16. Qb2 Bg4
17. b5 c5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Be2 Nce4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Nd4 Qe5 $17) 13. a3 Ne4
$1 14. b4 Ndf6 15. Ne5 Bf5 $1 {Black is supporting the e4-knight and the plan
is to exchange that bishop later.} 16. Rac1 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 (17. Bxf5 Nce4 18.
Qb2 g6 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 $17 20. b5 (20. Nf3 a6 21. a4 Nd6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb5][%cal
Rb4b5]} 22. Nd2 h5 23. Qa3 Kg7 $19) 20... c5 $17) 17... Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Ne4 19.
Nf3 (19. b5 c5 $19 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rd4c5,Rd4e5]}) 19... a6 20. Qb3 h5 21. a4
Nd6 {With a typical scenario where White doesn't have any counterplay and
Black will continue to improve the position on the kingside. The structure
with hxg3 is bad for White since the pawn on g3 serves as a hook to open up
White's king after an eventual h5-h4.} 22. Nd2 h4 23. gxh4 (23. g4 Qg5 24. Qd1
Re6 25. Qe2 Rae8 26. Rfe1 Rg6 27. Nf1 f5 28. f4 Qxg4 29. Qxg4 fxg4 $19) 23...
Qxh4 $19 24. Qd1 (24. g3 Qh3 $19) 24... Re6 25. g3 Qh3 26. Qf3 Rh6 27. Qg2 Qf5
28. Qf3 Qh7 29. Rfe1 Re8 30. Rc3 Ree6 31. b5 axb5 32. axb5 Ref6 33. Qg2 Nxb5
34. Ra1 g5 35. Ra8+ Kg7 36. Rc1 Rh3 $19 37. Nf3 Rfh6 38. Nh4 g4 $19 *

