{This is a good educational example of positions with the knight on d6.} 1. d4
d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bg3 {This move is
a mistake because after the trade on g3, White will recapture hxg3 and even
though the h-file will be open for White's rook on h1, there is no real flank
attack since the center is open. That's why White should realize that castling
short is better, and then later on, the pawn on g3 can serve as a hook to open
up the kingside.} Bxg3 8. hxg3 O-O 9. e3 Nc6 10. Bb5 Ne7 11. Bd3 Bf5 12. O-O
Bxd3 (12... c6 {Is also within the standard moves for Black.}) 13. Qxd3 Nc8 14.
Rac1 Nd6 $15 15. Nb5 Nfe8 {Getting ready to bring the other knight to d6.} (
15... c6 $15) 16. Ne5 c6 17. Nxd6 Nxd6 18. Qe2 (18. Qc2 Re8 $15) 18... Re8 19.
b4 a6 20. a4 f6 21. Nf3 Qd7 $36 22. Nd2 Qf5 23. Qf3 Qe6 $1 {Black should avoid
the queen trade! Black is the one who will organize an attack against White's
king, so it's better to keep the queens on the board.} (23... Qxf3 $2 {This is
a positional mistake. Nevertheless, in this particular position, Black is
better after 24.gxf3 a5!.}) 24. Rfe1 g6 25. Qd1 Kg7 26. Nb3 h5 27. Nc5 Qf7 $17
{Overprotecting the pawn on b7. Black is slowly improving the position and
building up an attack against White's king. In addition, White has no
counterplay.} (27... Qf5 $6 {Is a bit careless and allows White to play 28.b5
tactically.} 28. b5 axb5 29. axb5 cxb5 30. Nxb7 $11) 0-1

