1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 c6 $5 {After this
move, Black wants to play ...Bf5! since Qb3 can now be met with ...Qb6.} (6...
Bd6 $1 {Is also playable and good.} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 O-O 9. Qc2 (9. Bd3 {
Allows the move:} Bg4 {Black will trade the light-squared bishop eventually.
The goal is to get a position with a knight on d6 against one minor for White.}
10. h3 (10. O-O c6 11. Be2 Nbd7 12. Ne1 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Qe7 14. Nd3 Nb6 (14...
Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6] Is also possible.}) 15. Rac1 Nc4 16. b3 Nd6 17. Na4 Nd7 18.
Nac5 Rfe8 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Nc5 Qe7 $15) 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Re8 $1 {
Preventing any e4 ideas that White may have.} 12. O-O-O {Whenever White
castles long, Black gets a very good counterplay with a direct attack against
the White king!} (12. O-O c6 13. Rab1 Nbd7 14. b4 a6 15. a4 g6 {Improving the
position.} (15... Nb6 {This is another set-up if Black isn't on time to get a
knight on d6. The idea is to meet b5 with cxb5 axb5 and then a6-a5!}) 16. b5
axb5 17. axb5 c5 $15 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Bc2 Qe5 {With a good game for Black.})
12... Nc6 13. g4 Nb4 14. Bb1 Ne4 $36) 9... a6 $1 10. Bd3 Nc6 $1 11. a3 Bg4 12.
Nd2 Ne7 13. O-O Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g6,Gg4h5] Black is rerouting the bishop to g6.
} 14. Rfe1 Bg6 15. Bxg6 Nxg6 16. Na4 c6 17. Nc5 Qc7 18. b4 Ne7 19. h3 {[%cal
Ge7c8,Gc8d6]} Nc8 20. Rac1 Nd6 21. a4 Qe7 22. Qb3 Rfe8 (22... Qd8 {This move
is just to show an idea for White. White can push b5 now because the knight is
overloaded defending the b5-square and the b7-pawn.} 23. b5 axb5 24. axb5 Nxb5
$2 25. Nxb7) 23. Rc2 Nd7 24. Nxd7 $2 Qxd7 $17 25. Qd3 Re6 26. Kh1 Rae8 27. Nb3
Rg6 28. Nc5 Qe7 29. Rg1 Qg5 $36 (29... Qh4 $36)) (6... Bf5 7. Qb3 $1 {This
move is always an issue when Black plays Bf5 quickly.}) 7. Qc2 {Preventing Bf5.
} (7. e3 Bf5 8. Qb3 (8. Bd3 {Here are some sample lines which show the typical
ideas in this variation.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 (9... Bd6 {Is also possible.}) 10.
h3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Nb6 13. Nd2 Re8 (13... Bd6 {Is also good.}) 14. Rac1
Nc8 15. Rfe1 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 $11 {Black is already a bit more comfortable.})
(8. Ne5 Be7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Nxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. h3 Nb6 13. b3 Bd6 14.
Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qc2 Qe7 16. Rac1 Nc8 17. Rfe1 Nd6 18. f3 Rfe8 19. Nf2 (19. e4 $2
{Loses a pawn for White.} dxe4 20. fxe4 Nfxe4 21. Nxe4 Nxe4 22. Nf2 f5 $17)
19... Rad8 $11 {Black is ready for White's e4 push, and whenever it's played,
the central pawns e4 and d4 will become targets for Black's pieces.}) 8... Qb6
{Black is already fighting to take over.}) 7... Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e3 O-O 10.
Bd3 {Whenever Bf5 or Bg4 aren't possible or they are ineffective (on Bg4 White
has Ne5), Black's plan is to control the e4-square and later on jump Ne4!} (10.
O-O-O $2 {Castling long is always very risky for White. The computer gives a
big advantage to Black, and the way to proceed is to push the a and b-pawns.}
b5 $1 11. Kb1 Na6 $1 $17 (11... a5 $5 {Is interesting, but ...Na6 is better in
this case instead.}) 12. a3 (12. Ka1 Nb4 13. Qc1 Bf5 14. Ne1 a5 $19) 12... b4
$40 {The attack is very strong.}) 10... Re8 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rab1 Qe7 $1 13. a3
Ne4 14. Nd2 Nxd2 $1 (14... Nd6 $5) 15. Qxd2 Nb6 $1 16. b4 Be6 17. a4 a6 $3 {
Remember this set-up! White can't play 18.b5 because of 18...cxb5 19.axb5 a5!
and if White plays 18.a5?! instead, it would block the queenside forever and
White will have no play, while Black can improve the position on the kingside.}
18. Rfc1 (18. b5 $2 cxb5 19. axb5 a5 $17) 18... Nc4 $1 19. Bxc4 (19. Qa2 b5 $15
) 19... dxc4 20. e4 b5 $15 *

