1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 h6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bxd6 (7. Be5
c6 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 Bxe5 (9... Qe7) 10. Nxe5 Nbd7 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. O-O Qe7 (
12... Ne8) 13. Qc2 Ne8 14. Rae1 Nd6 15. b3 Be6) 7... Qxd6 8. e3 Bf5 $5 {
This is an interesting move, but Black needs to be ready against 9.Qb3 since
the b7-pawn becomes vulnerable.} 9. Bd3 $6 (9. Qb3 $1 O-O $1 10. Qxb7 (10. Rc1
Qb6 11. Qxb6 axb6 $11) 10... Nc6 11. Qa6 (11. Nb5 $4 Qb4+ $19) 11... Rab8 12.
Qa3 Nb4 $19) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. O-O O-O {Getting the king to safety
is a priority, while ...c6 can be played later.} (11... c6 12. e4 $13) 12. Rac1
c6 13. a3 a5 $6 {Black never wants to play a5 in order to prevent b4 since the
a or b-files will open up after an eventual b2-b4, and White is the one
playing on the queenside. Black should wait on the queenside and meet the
minority attack b4-a4 with ...a6.} (13... Qe7 $1 {Freeing the d6-square for a
knight and gaining more control over the e4-square.} 14. b4 Ne4 15. Nd2 Nxd2 $1
16. Qxd2 Nb6 $15) 14. Nd2 Rfe8 15. Na4 Re7 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. Rxc5 a4 18. Rfc1 h5
19. Qf5 g6 20. Qh3 Kg7 21. Qg3 Qe6 22. R5c2 Qf5 23. h3 Ra6 24. Qf3 Qd3 25. Nb1
Ne4 26. Qe2 Qxe2 27. Rxe2 Nd6 28. Nd2 Rb6 29. Rc2 f6 30. Kf1 g5 $17 31. g3 Nf5
32. Nb1 Nd6 33. Nc3 Ra6 34. Nb1 Ra8 35. Kg2 Kg6 36. Nd2 Rh8 37. Nb1 h4 38. g4
f5 39. gxf5+ Kxf5 40. Nc3 b5 41. Na2 Nc4 42. Nb4 Re6 43. Nd3 g4 44. Nf4 Ree8
45. Kh2 Rhg8 46. hxg4+ Rxg4 47. Re1 Rxf4 0-1

