1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 h6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8.
e3 O-O 9. Qb3 c6 $1 10. Be2 Qe7 $1 {Protecting the b7-pawn and allowing the
c8-bishop to develop. In addition, this move frees the d6-square for a knight
later on, and strengthens the control over the e4-square even further.} (10...
Qc7 $5 11. O-O Bf5 $1 (11... Qb6 12. Qc2) 12. Qd1 (12. Rac1 Qb6) 12... Qe7 13.
Rc1 Nbd7 14. Nh4 Be6 (14... Bh7) 15. Bd3 Nb6 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Nc4 18. b3
Nd6) (10... Nbd7 $5 11. O-O Qe7 12. Rac1 Ne8 $1 13. Qc2 Nd6 14. Rfd1 (14. b4 a6
15. a4 b5 $36 {The usual way to meet b4-b5 from White.} (15... Nb6 $36 {
This is also possible, it's another way of meeting the b4-b5 push from White.}
16. b5 (16. Ne5 Bf5 $11) 16... cxb5 17. axb5 a5 $1 {The typical idea to meet
White's b5-push.} 18. Ne5 Be6 19. Qb3 Rfc8 $15)) 14... Nf6 15. Ne5 Bf5 16. Qd2
Nfe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Qe1 f6 19. Nd3 Rae8 20. Qb4 (20. Nc5 Nd6 {Black avoids
the knight trade and brings the knight to its best square.}) 20... Nd6 $1 {
Black doesn't want to trade queens because Black is the one who will attack
White's king eventually.}) 11. O-O Bg4 12. Rac1 Ne4 13. Rfd1 Nd6 $36 {With a
standard position where Black managed to get the knight to d6.} 0-1

