{This is a great game by Kasparov with the knight on d6 typical positions. It
doesn't matter that it comes from a different line since the position arising
is very similar.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 $6 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Qc2
(6. Bf4 Bf5 7. e3 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. h3
Qe7 13. Rfd1 Ne4 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Nb6 16. b3 Nc8 17. Rac1 Nd6 $15 {
A sample line, reaching the standard position with the knight on d6.}) 6... Na6
7. a3 Nc7 8. Bg5 g6 9. e3 Bf5 {Kasparov uses the opportunity to play this move
immediately.} (9... Bg7 $2 10. Bd3 $16 {Preventing ...Bf5.}) 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11.
Qxd3 Be7 $1 12. O-O O-O 13. b4 $2 (13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. b4 Ne6 $11 {Since Black
is not on time with Nd6, Black prepares to meet 15.b5 with 15...c5!} (14... Ne8
{Black is not on time to reach the ideal set-up with the knight on d6 and to
prevent b4-b5.} 15. b5 Nd6 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. Nd2 $14)) 13... Ne4 $1 14. Bf4 (
14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nd2 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Nb5 17. Qd3 Nd6 18. a4 a6 19. Rfc1 Qd7 20.
h3 Rae8 {Black should only play b7-b5 when White threatens to play b4-b5. In
the meantime, Black can improve the position on the kingside.} 21. Nb1 h5 22.
Nc3 b5 23. axb5 axb5 $11) 14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 (15. Bxc7 $1 {White should take
the opportunity to capture both knights and eliminate the possibility for
Black to get a knight to d6.}) 15... Bd6 $1 (15... Nb5 16. Qb3 Nd6 $2 {This
allows White to eliminate this strong knight.} 17. Bxd6 Bxd6 18. b5 cxb5 $2 19.
Qxb5 b6 20. a4 $16) 16. Bxd6 (16. Bg3 $2 Bxg3 17. hxg3 {The pawn on g3 will
serve as a hook for h5-h4 in order to open files for an attack on White's king
later. That's why White should capture the bishop on d6 instead.} Nb5 18. Qd3
Nd6 19. a4 a6 20. Nd2 Re8 $17 {White doesn't have an active plan and Black
will improve the position further with moves like Kg7, h5, and Black will aim
to play h4 eventually.} (20... h5 $17)) 16... Nb5 $1 17. Qb3 Nxd6 18. a4 a6 $1
19. Ne5 Re8 20. Rfe1 Qg5 21. h3 Kg7 22. Qc2 Re6 23. Rac1 Rae8 24. Qb1 Qh5 25.
Qb3 f6 26. Nd3 g5 27. Qd1 (27. Nc5 R6e7 28. a5 $2 Ne4 $5 {Once White closes
the queenside with the move a4-a5, it's okay for Black to trade the knights
since White won't have any open files and targets on the queenside for the
major pieces.} (28... Kh8 {With the queenside closed, the game is one-sided.
White doesn't have any counterplay and Black will build up an attack on
White's king.}) 29. Nxe4 Rxe4 30. b5 {White has to try this move, otherwise
the game would be White waiting passively to be defeated on the kingside.} axb5
31. a6 bxa6 32. Rxc6 g4 33. hxg4 Rxg4 $13) 27... Qg6 28. Qc2 R6e7 $1 {A
prophylactic from Nc5 and a queen trade.} (28... h5 {Is a bit careless since
it would allow the trade of queens. Black is the one attacking, so keeping the
queens on the board is in Black's favor.} 29. Nc5 R6e7 30. Qxg6+) 29. Red1 (29.
Nc5 Qf7 $15) 29... h5 $1 30. Qb1 h4 $1 31. Qc2 g4 32. Nf4 (32. hxg4 Qxg4 33.
Nf4 h3 34. Nxh3 Rh8 35. Nf4 Qh4 36. Qg6+ Kf8 $19) 32... Qxc2 33. Rxc2 g3 34.
Rd3 (34. fxg3 hxg3 (34... Nf5 $19) 35. Nh5+ Kg6 36. Nxg3 Rxe3 37. Nf1 Rb3 38.
b5 axb5 39. axb5 Nxb5 $19) 34... Kh6 $1 35. Kf1 Kg5 36. Ne2 Nc4 37. Rcc3 Nb2
38. Rd2 Nxa4 39. Rb3 Nb6 40. Ng1 Nc4 41. Nf3+ Kh5 42. Rdd3 a5 43. bxa5 Ra8 44.
Rd1 Rxa5 45. Re1 b5 46. Re2 Ra1+ 47. Re1 Rea7 48. fxg3 Rxe1+ 49. Kxe1 Ra1+ 50.
Ke2 hxg3 51. Ne1 Ra2+ 52. Kd1 Rd2+ 53. Kc1 Re2 54. Kd1 Rxe3 55. Rxe3 Nxe3+ 56.
Ke2 Nf5 57. Nc2 Nh4 58. Nb4 Nxg2 59. Kf3 Nh4+ 60. Kxg3 Nf5+ 61. Kf4 Nxd4 62.
Ke3 Nf5+ 0-1

