{This is a very good game where Black played the correct ideas, but later on,
Black made mistakes and lost on time. This was a blitz game after all.} 1. d4
h6 {The move order doesn't matter as it's a blitz game, but the game will soon
transpose into the Queen's Gambit.} 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6
$5 6. e3 Bd6 $5 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 Ne7 $1 {Black is preparing Bf5.} 9. Nge2 $6
(9. Qf3 $1 {Preventing Bf5 is a good idea for White.} Nd7 10. Nge2 O-O $14)
9... Bf5 10. O-O O-O 11. Ng3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nd7 13. Nce2 (13. Nf5 Nxf5 14. Qxf5
Nb6 15. Rac1 Qe7 16. b3 Nc8 17. Qc2 $15) 13... Rad8 14. Rac1 Rfe8 15. Nf4 Nf6
16. a3 Qd7 $1 17. b4 Nc8 18. Rc2 (18. Nf5 Ne4 $15) (18. Qf5 Qe7 {Keeping the
queens on the board.}) 18... Nd6 $15 19. Rfc1 Nfe4 $5 (19... a6 {Is also
possible.}) (19... a5 $5 {Is playable in this position because the White
knights are on the other side of the board and overall, White's pieces are not
well placed to meet this strike on the queenside.} 20. bxa5 Ra8 21. Qc3 Ra7 22.
Nd3 Qc7 23. a4 (23. Nc5 Rxa5 $15) 23... Rxa5 $15) 20. a4 $2 {This is a mistake
because it allows Black to damage White's pawn structure in front of White's
king.} (20. Nxe4 Rxe4 21. a4 a6 22. Qf1 Nc4 $6 (22... g6 $17 23. Nd3 Qf5 24.
Nc5 Re7 25. Qd3 Qg5 $15 (25... Qf6 $15)) (22... Qe7 23. Nd3 Re6 24. Nf4 Rf6 $15
) 23. Nd3 Re7 24. Nc5 Qd6 25. e4 $5 a5 26. e5 Qg6 27. bxa5 Nxa5 28. Rc3 b6 29.
Rg3 Qf5 30. Nd3 Nb3 31. Rxc6 Nxd4 32. Rxb6 Rc8 33. h4 Qe4 34. Re3 Qxh4 35. Rb4
Rc4 36. Rb8+ Kh7 $11) 20... Nxg3 $1 21. hxg3 a6 $17 22. Qb3 (22. Rb2 g6 {
White can't push b4-b5, so Black is making useful moves that improve the
position.}) 22... g6 23. Nd3 h5 24. Nc5 Qe7 (24... Qf5 {Is also playable.} 25.
Qd3 Qg5 26. b5 axb5 27. axb5 cxb5 28. Ra1 Kg7 29. Ra7 Re7 30. Rca2 h4 $19) 25.
Qd3 Kg7 $17 1-0

