1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 Bd6 6. Bxd6 (6. Bg3 Bxg3 7. hxg3
O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. O-O b6
14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Rd1 Rxd1+ 17. Nxd1 Kf8 (17... Bxf3 $5 {Black
is playing for a win after this trade, as White's bishop is not very good.})
18. Nc3 Nfe4 19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. a3 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Nb7 $15 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb7d6]
}) 6... Qxd6 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 10. O-O Nc6 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Qe2
Rd8 13. Rfd1 Bd7 14. Rac1 Be8 (14... Ne5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. h3 Bc6 17. Rxd8+
Rxd8 18. Rd1 Qc7 (18... Rc8 $36) 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. Qd3 Qxd3 21. Bxd3 $11) 15.
Bb3 Qa5 {The queen remains on the 5th rank in order to for Black to play Ne5
at some point.} 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. Rd1 Rxd1+ 18. Qxd1 Qd8 19. Qxd8 Nxd8 {
This is an equal endgame where both sides have chances. It's very instructive
to see how Black takes over.} 20. Bc2 b6 21. Ne4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Kf8 23. Bc2 Bc6
{Black would like to trade the light-squared bishop for the knight in general,
not just in this case where it would double White's pawns. Imagining if the
trade happened and the pawn was still on g2, the position would be objectively
equal, but Black will put a knight on d6 and White will have a long way ahead
to make a draw.} 24. a3 $2 Bxf3 $17 25. gxf3 e5 $15 (25... g5 $15) (25... Nb7
26. f4 Nd6 $15) *

