[EventDate "2023.01.30"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. g3 Nc6 $1 {It's very important for
Black to play Nc6! immediately, before Bd6. This move order prevents all
dangerous ideas with g3-g4, as well as Qc2 with g3-g4.} 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {
The main position for the Catalan with ...h6 and Nc3. In this position, 8.b3
is the best move for White, 8.c5 is playable, and all the other moves lead to
an advantage for Black, usually by following the typical plan of ...dxc4 and ..
.e5! The positions can be very similar, so it's more important to learn the
ideas instead of the exact theory.} 8. b3 {This is by far the best move for
White. Now, Black can continue with 8...dxc4 and 9...e5, or choose a less
theoretical option which is 8...Re8, with the idea to capture ...dxc4 and then
to play ... e5 next. The full analysis can be found in the theoretical chapter.
} (8. Qc2 {This shows Black's plan of playing dxc4 and then e6-e5.} dxc4 9. e4
e5 {This is the typical way to meet e4, and Black has a good position.}) *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "CATALAN h6"]
[Black "with Nc3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D37"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "20"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 (3. Nf3 h6 {Black can also choose to play 3...Nf6,
but it would allow White the option to play 4.Bg5, while the other moves from
White will transpose.} 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 {Usually White plays the Catalan
without the move Nc3.} (5. Nc3 Nc6 $1 {If there is g3 and Nc3, Black can play
Nc6! which would transpose to the main line, however, Black doesn't play Nc6
until White plays Nc3 (and with g3 on the board)!}) 5... Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3
{Transposes to the main line.}) 3... h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. g3 $1 {White can choose
whether to play the Catalan with or without Nc3, and in this chapter, the
Catalan with Nc3 will be examined. The knight doesn't usually go to c3 in the
Catalan, but White can choose to play it, or White already has the knight
committed to c3 from various move orders.} Bd6 $6 {This transposes to the main
line which arises from the right move order with 5...Nc6.} (5... Nc6 $1 {
It's very important for Black to play Nc6! immediately, before Bd6. This move
order prevents all dangerous ideas with g3-g4, as well as Qc2 with g3-g4.} 6.
Bg2 (6. Qc2 $2 dxc4 7. e3 (7. e4 $2 Nxd4 $17) 7... Nb4 $1 (7... Bd6 $5 {
Entering a typical position where White has played the move g3 which is bad
for White, however, 7...Nb4! is better than 7...Bd6.} 8. Bxc4 e5 $15 9. d5 $2
Nb4 $17 10. Qb1 (10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qd1 Bg4 12. Be2 (12. a3 $2 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nc2+
$19) 12... Nbxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. O-O Nf6 $19) 10... Bh3 11. Rg1 c6 12. dxc6
Nxc6 $17) 8. Qd1 Nd3+ $15 9. Bxd3 cxd3 10. Qxd3 a6 11. O-O b5 12. e4 Bb7 $15) (
6. g4 $2 Nxg4 {The bishop is still on f8, so g4 simply loses a pawn for White.}
) 6... Bd6 {Transposes to the main line arising from 5...Bd6.}) 6. Bg2 (6. Qc2
Nc6 $1 {even now! as fast Nc6 as possible!}) 6... O-O 7. O-O Nc6 $1 {The main
position for the Catalan with ...h6 and Nc3. In this position, 8.b3 is the
best move for White, 8.c5 is playable, and all the other moves lead to an
advantage for Black, usually by following the typical plan of ...dxc4 and ...
e5! The positions can be very similar, so it's more important to learn the
ideas instead of the exact theory.} 8. b3 $1 {8.b3 is by far the best move for
White. Now, Black can continue with 8...dxc4 and 9...e5, or choose a less
theoretical option which is 8...Re8, with the idea to capture ...dxc4 and then
to play ...e5 next.} (8. e3 $6 {This is a very common mistake. Black is going
to capture the pawn on c4 and play ...e5 after that! Black is already better.}
dxc4 9. Qa4 (9. Nd2 $6 e5 $1 10. Bxc6 $2 (10. Nxc4 exd4 11. exd4 Bg4 $1 12. f3
(12. Qd2 Qd7 $36) 12... Be6 $15 13. Ne3 Ne7 14. f4 Nf5 (14... Qc8)) (10. d5 Na5
$15 11. Qe2 Bg4 {Provoking f3.} 12. f3 (12. Bf3 Bxf3 $19 {Distracting a piece
from pressuring the c4-pawn, so White won't win it back.}) 12... Bd7 13. Nxc4
Nxc4 14. Qxc4 c6 $17) 10... bxc6 $19 11. Nxc4 (11. dxe5 Bxe5 $19 12. Nxc4 Bxc3
13. bxc3 Ba6 $19) 11... e4 $17) (9. Qe2 e5 10. Qxc4 (10. d5 Na5 $1 {10...Ne7
is a safe way to play, but this is much better! In general, when Black is
faced with this type of choice, the computer usually prefers Na5 or Nb4 in
comparison to Ne7, but of course, it should always be calculated.} 11. e4 a6
