{This is a game with the wrong move order - 5...Bd6?!, from which it can be
seen what happens if White plays correctly.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4.
Nc3 h6 5. g3 Bd6 {This is inaccurate and has been discussed in the theoretical
chapter.} (5... Nc6 $1 {This is the recommended move order which doesn't allow
what happened in the game.} 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {With the starting
theoretical position.}) 6. a3 {This is a clever waiting move, although 6.Qc2
is probably better.} (6. Qc2 dxc4 (6... O-O 7. g4 {White is using the h6-pawn
as a hook to open up the g-file towards the Black king on g8.}) 7. e4 $16 {
This is a sign of a bad position, Black should be able to meet e4 with e6-e5,
which is not possible in this position.}) 6... O-O ({Black should have played:
} 6... Nc6 7. c5 Be7 8. b4 O-O $14) 7. g4 {The computer may show only a slight
advantage for White, but the position is difficult to handle for Black in
practice.} Nxg4 (7... Ne4 $5 {The best move in the position.} 8. g5 h5 $13) (
7... dxc4 $2 8. g5 (8. e4 $16) 8... hxg5 9. Bxg5 $16 {White will have a very
strong attack against Black's king.}) 8. Rg1 e5 {Black is opening up the
center while the White king is still uncastled, although the tactics are in
White's favor.} 9. cxd5 Re8 {White is better and there is no need for Black to
allow these complications.} 10. Ne4 Bf8 11. h3 exd4 12. Qxd4 Qe7 13. Nc3 Ne5
14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Rxe5 16. Bxh6 Rh5 17. Bf4 c6 18. Rd1 Bxh3 19. Ne4 Rf5
20. Bxh3 Rxf4 21. Bc8 1-0

