1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. g3 Bd6 6. Bg2 {White doesn't take
advantage of Black's inaccurate move order.} O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. e3 $6 dxc4 9.
Nd2 $6 (9. Qe2 e5 10. Qxc4 (10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qxc4 c6 13. Rd1 Qe7
14. Qe2 Bg4 15. Bf3 $6 h5 $17) 10... Re8 {If Black doesn't have to capture on
d4, it's usually a good idea to postpone it since it creates the extra option
of playing e5-e4, however, Black shouldn't play 10...e4 immediately because
the pawn falls after 11.Nd2.} 11. d5 $2 Na5 $1 12. Qe2 c6 (12... Bb4 13. e4 c6
$15) (12... e4 13. Nd2 Bf5 $17) 13. dxc6 Nxc6 $15 {Black is simply better
because of White's bad bishop on c1.} 14. e4 {Giving additional scope to the
c1-bishop, but here Black is better due to the bad bishop on g2.} Bg4 $15) 9...
Na5 (9... e5 $1 {The correct move!} 10. Nxc4 (10. Bxc6 $6 {The light-squared
bishop has a very important role in defending the squares around the king on
g1, trading it for the knight is a mistake.} bxc6 11. Nxc4 (11. dxe5 Bxe5 $19
12. Nxc4 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Ba6 $19) 11... e4 $17 {Black's light-squared bishop
will be extremely strong since the light squares around White's king are very
weak, and in addition, the bishop on c1 has no good future.}) 10... exd4 11.
exd4 Bg4 12. f3 Be6 13. Ne3 Ne7 $15) 10. Qa4 b6 11. Bxa8 Bd7 12. Qc2 Qxa8 13.
e4 e5 14. Nf3 Nc6 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. f3 Bd4+ 18. Kg2 Qc8 19. Rd1
Bc5 20. Bf4 Re8 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Be6 23. Rd2 b5 24. Rad1 Bb6 25. Qc3 c5
26. a3 a5 27. Rd6 b4 28. Qe3 Qb7 29. Bxh6 gxh6 30. Qxh6 Ba7 31. Qg5+ Kf8 32.
Qh6+ Kg8 33. h4 Qe7 34. h5 Bb8 35. R6d2 Qf8 36. Qg5+ Qg7 37. Qh4 c3 38. h6
Qxg3+ 39. Qxg3+ Bxg3 40. Rd8 Rxd8 41. Rxd8+ Kh7 42. bxc3 b3 43. Kxg3 Kxh6 44.
