1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. g3 Bd6 6. cxd5 $2 {This is a wrong
move after which Black immediately gains a preferable position.} exd5 7. Bg2
O-O 8. O-O Nc6 $5 {8...c6 is a better move.} (8... c6 $1 {Black is already
better and will continue with Bf5 and Nbd7 next. As a general rule in the
Carlsbad structure, Black puts a knight on d6 when the dark-squared bishop is
exchanged, otherwise, the bishop stays on that square.} 9. Qc2 Nbd7 $15) 9. Bf4
(9. Nb5 {Black can simply ignore the threat since after Nxd6, Black will
recapture with the pawn - ...cxd6!}) 9... Bxf4 10. gxf4 Ne7 {Jacobson played
the correct way against 9.Bf4.} 11. Ne5 c6 {The knight is well placed on e7,
from where it can go to f5 and eye up the h4-square which was weakened by gxf4
earlier. This means that the other knight from f6 should be transferred to the
d6-square.} 12. Kh1 Nf5 13. e3 Nh4 14. Rg1 $15 Bf5 15. Bf1 Ne4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4+
17. f3 Bh7 18. Qe1 Nf5 19. Bd3 Qd6 20. Bxf5 Bxf5 21. Qh4 Kh7 22. Rg3 f6 23.
Rag1 Rg8 24. Nf7 Qe6 25. Rxg7+ 1-0

