{This is a great game by Black which shows the typical ideas in the pawn
structure which arises.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 h6 {This is a blitz game and the
starting move order of the game is irrelevant to our study.} 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2
e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. cxd5 $6 exd5 9. Bf4 $6 Bxf4 10. gxf4 Ne7
$1 11. Ne5 c6 12. h3 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6] The f6-knight will be well-placed on
the d6-square.} 13. Kh2 Nd6 14. Rg1 {White doesn't have any attack on the
g-file.} f6 15. Nd3 Bf5 $17 {Black can try to prepare and push g7-g5!} (15...
Nef5 $17) 16. Bf3 Ng6 17. e3 Nh4 18. Bg4 Bxd3 $1 19. Qxd3 f5 20. Bh5 Qf6 21.
Rg3 Kh8 22. Rag1 Rg8 $17 23. Rg6 (23. Bg6 Ne4 (23... a5 $15) 24. Nxe4 fxe4 25.
Qe2 a5 $15 (25... Nf3+ $15)) 23... Nxg6 24. Rxg6 Qe7 $19 25. Rxd6 Qxd6 26. Ne2
g6 27. Bf3 Raf8 28. Ng3 Qf6 29. a3 Rc8 30. Qc3 Rgd8 31. Qa5 a6 32. Qb4 Rd7 33.
Qb6 Qd8 34. Qb4 Qe7 35. Qb6 Kg7 36. Be2 c5 37. dxc5 Qxc5 38. Qb3 d4 39. Qa4
Rcd8 40. e4 d3 41. Bf3 Qxf2+ 42. Bg2 Qxf4 43. Qb4 Qe5 44. exf5 gxf5 45. Qb6 f4
46. Ne4 f3+ 47. Kg1 fxg2 48. Nf2 d2 49. Qg6+ Kxg6 0-1

