1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 h6 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 {This is the Catalan without Nc3.
It's important that in this position, Black plays 5...Bd6 and not 5...Nc6. The
move Nc6 is played only after White has played g3 and Nc3.} Bd6 $1 6. O-O O-O {
This is the starting position of this variation.} 7. Qc2 {This is very similar
to 7.b3.} (7. Nbd2 {The moves 7.Nbd2 and 7.Nfd2 can be both met with:} c5 $1 {
Which is likely to lead to a better version for Black from the standard
positions with an isolated pawn.}) 7... b6 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nb5 Nc6
11. Nxd6 cxd6 $132 {This is just one version of the positions with doubled
d-pawns that will be discussed in the analysis and the games. The point is
that these positions are very difficult for White to play practically, while
Black has a choice of many good moves and plans to choose from.} *

