1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 h6 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 {In this chapter, the Catalan
without Nc3 will be analyzed. It's important that in this position, Black
plays 5...Bd6 and not 5...Nc6. The move Nc6 is played only after White has
played g3 and Nc3.} (5. Nc3 Nc6 $1 {In the Catalan with Nc3, Black must play
Nc6! quickly!}) 5... Bd6 6. O-O O-O (6... Nc6 $2 {This is good only after
White plays the move Nc3! Black's plan with Nc6 is to capture on c4 and play
e6-e5. When the White knight is still on b1, it can be developed to d2 and it
will be aimed against this plan (with the idea to recapture Nxc4 and control
the e5-square).}) 7. b3 $1 {This is very similar to 7.Qc2.} (7. Nfd2 $6 c5 $1
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nc3 {White managed to attack the
isolated pawn but lost a lot of tempi with the knight.} d4 $1 12. Na4 Nc6 13.
Nxb6 axb6 $1 14. Bxc6 bxc6 $15 15. Qxd4 (15. Nxd4 c5 16. Nc2 (16. Nf3 Qe7 $15)
16... Qe7 $36 (16... Qc7 $5 17. Bf4 Qb7 $1 $36)) 15... Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5]
Black has great compensation in this position since White's light squares
around the king on g1 are weak, and the knight on b3 is misplaced.} (15... Bd7
$5 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 16. Bf4 Qb7 17. f3 c5 18. Qd2 (18. Qc3 Nd5 $17) (18. Qf2
Nd5 19. Bd2 Be6 $15) 18... Nd5 19. Rfd1 Be6 $15) (7. Nbd2 $6 {Surprisingly,
this is not a good move! Black should play 7...c5 which is likely to reach a
position with an isolated pawn for Black.} c5 $1 {This is a very good move to
remember, both after 7.Nbd2 and 7.Nfd2.} (7... b6 {Is also good since it's
likely to transpose to the main line starting from 7.b3, although 7...c5! is
better in this exact position.}) 8. cxd5 (8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. a3 a5 $1 10. b3 b6
11. Bb2 Bb7 {The knight on d2 is misplaced and has no good square to go to
from d2.} 12. cxd5 Bxd5 $132) (8. b3 Nc6 $132) 8... exd5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nb3
Bb6 11. Nbd4 {This is a better version for Black from the standard isolated
pawn since White can't play Bg5. In addition, one of White's knights should be
on d4 to block the pawn, and the other one on c3 in order to attack it, here
however, White doesn't have any pressure on the d5-pawn at all.} Re8 12. b3 Nc6
$1 (12... Na6 $5 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5e4]} 13. Bb2 Nc5 14. Rc1 Nce4 $132) 13. Bb2
Ne4 14. Rc1 Qd6 $11) (7. Qc2 {This is similar to 7.b3 and White is likely to
play it sooner or later.} b6 $1 (7... Nc6 $2 {Nc6 is good only after White has
played Nc3.} 8. Nbd2 $1 $14 dxc4 (8... a5 9. e4 Nb4 10. Qb1 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4
12. Qxe4 $16) 9. Nxc4 Bd7 10. e4 $16 (10. Nxd6 $2 cxd6 $11)) 8. b3 $5 (8. Ne5
$6 c5 $1 9. Rd1 Bb7 $36) (8. Nc3 {This is a different position with Nc3 where
Black has already played ...b6, so Black shouldn't play Nc6 here. Black should
continue with 8...Bb7 instead.} Bb7 9. cxd5 {In 95% of the time, this is the
correct recapture.} (9. Ne5 $2 c5 $1 $15 {The knight on e5 is unstable.} 10.
Bf4 cxd4 11. Nb5 Bxe5 12. Bxe5 Nc6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Bxd5 Rac8 (
15... Nb4 $19) 16. Qb3 Rfd8 17. Rac1 a6 18. Bxc6 Rxc6 19. Rxc6 Qxc6 20. f3 Qxb5
21. Qc2 Re8 22. Kf2 Qc5 23. Qd3 Bc6 24. Rd1 Bb5 25. Qxd4 Rxe2+ 26. Kg1 Re1+ 27.
Kf2 Rxd1 {0-1 TWICE_Chou_Tzuyu-come2life/https://lichess.org/USzcDbf0 2022/[,
ÃéÜííçò]}) (9. Nb5 $2 dxc4 10. Qxc4 a6 11. Nxd6 cxd6 $15) 9... exd5 {
White has many move orders so it's more important to remember the ideas in the
position! When Black has already played ...b6 and White captures on d5 early,
Black wants to develop the knight to c6.} 10. Nb5 (10. Bf4 $6 Bxf4 $1 {It's
important that the rook is not on e8 yet because now, Black can follow up with
the typical idea of Nc6-Ne7, and Ne8! with a good play for Black.} 11. gxf4 Nc6
$1 12. Rac1 Ne7 13. Ne5 (13. e3 Ne8 14. Ne5 Nd6 15. Ne2 c6 16. Ng3 (16. Bh3 Bc8
$1 17. Bxc8 Rxc8 $15) 16... Rc8 17. Kh1 Rc7 18. b3 Bc8 $36) 13... Ne8 14. e3
Nd6 15. Ne2 (15. Qb3 c6 16. Qc2 (16. Rfd1 Kh8 $15) 16... Qe8 17. Rfd1 f6 18.
Nf3 Bc8 $15) 15... f6 (15... c6 16. Ng3 Rc8 17. Rfd1 Rc7 $11) 16. Nf3 c6 17.
Kh1 Bc8 18. Ng3 Qe8 19. Rg1 Kh8 20. Nh4 g5 $15) 10... Nc6 $1 11. Nxd6 cxd6 $1
$132 {Regardless of the computer evaluation, this is a very difficult position
for White to play practically. Black has a typical counterplay on the light
squares and the moves are very easy, such as Re8, b5, a5, Qd7, Ba6, and so on.}
12. Bf4 (12. Bd2 Qd7 (12... Re8 13. Bc3 a5 14. e3 b5 $36) (12... Rc8 {Is also
possible.}) 13. Rfc1 a5 14. Qd1 Ba6 (14... Rfe8 15. e3 Ba6 16. Be1 (16. Bf1
Bxf1 17. Qxf1 Ne7 $15) 16... b5 (16... Ne4 $5) 17. a3 (17. Nd2 b4 $36) 17... b4
18. axb4 axb4 19. Nd2 Bb5 20. b3 $13) 15. e3 Rfc8 16. Be1 Rc7 17. Rc2 Rac8 18.
Rac1 Bc4 19. b3 Ba6 20. h3 Nb4 $11) (12. Be3 Re8 13. Rac1 a5 14. Rfd1 Rc8 15.
Qb1 Ba6 $132) 12... Re8 13. Rfe1 Rc8 14. Qa4 a6 15. Qa3 Ne4 16. h4 b5 $1 {
This leads to the game where Daniel Dardha was White.} (16... g5 $5 {This is
also possible.}) (16... Na5 $1 17. b3 Nc6 $1 $15 {This is the computer's idea,
to provoke b3 and after that push the b6-pawn with b5-b4.} 18. Rac1 b5 19. Qb2
b4 (19... Qf6 $15) 20. a3 (20. Bd2 a5 21. Rc2 Qf6 $15) 20... a5 $15)) (8. Rd1
Bb7 {Intending Nbd7 next, except if White decides to capture on d5, in that
case the knight will be developed on c6.} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Nc6 $1 {
Important rule: after White the captures cxd5 and ...exd5 are included, Black
wants to develop the knight to c6!} 11. Nb5 (11. Bf4 Bxf4 12. gxf4 Ne7 13. Rac1
Ne8 $132 {[%cal Ge8d6,Gc7c6,Gb7c8,Gc8f5,Ya8c8,Yc8c7] Black's idea is to play
Nd6, c6, and reroute the bishop to f5 via c8. If it's necessary in order to
avoid any tactics and defend the c6-pawn, Rc8-Rc7 can be played too. If there
is a White knight on e5, after Black plays Nd6 and c6, the idea to kick that
knight back can be Qe8 in order to control the g6-square, and then f7-f6!})
11... Re8 12. Nxd6 cxd6 $36) (8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Nb5 Nc6 11. Nxd6 cxd6
$36) 8... Bb7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Nc3 (10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nc3 {Black has a choice
whether to play 11...a6 which prevents Nb5, or 11...Re8 which ignores Nb5-Nxd6
with the intention to recapture ...cxd6.} (11. Nbd2 Re8 12. e3 c5 13. dxc5 bxc5
{Black has a good position with the hanging pawns since the knight on d2 is
misplaced. That knight should have been on c3 in order to put pressure on the
d5-pawn.}) 11... a6 12. Rac1 Re8 13. Nh4 {If White tries to capture the bishop
on d6 with the knight from f3, Black needs to be careful since after ...cxd6,
the knight from c3 is active, putting pressure on the d5-pawn and controlling
the e4-square. In addition, the bishop from g2 becomes active since the knight
from f3 blocked the bishop's view. In conclusion, Black shouldn't allow the
trade on d6 when White is offering the knight from f3.}) 10... a6 11. cxd5 exd5
12. Rac1 Re8 13. Nh4 (13. Rfe1 Qe7 14. e3 Ne4 $15) 13... Rc8 14. Nf5 Bf8 $132)
(7. c5 $5 {White pushed c5 too early but at least it's with tempo.} Be7 8. b4
$1 (8. Nc3 $2 b6 {8...Nc6 would have transposed to a position previously
analyzed, however, 8...b6 is a better move.} 9. cxb6 axb6 $15) 8... b6 $1 $132
9. Qc2 $1 (9. Nc3 $2 a5 $17 {White is not on time to solidify the pawn
structure with a3 since it loses a pawn after ...axb4.}) (9. Bb2 a5 10. a3 Nc6
$1 11. b5 Na7 $15 12. cxb6 Nxb5 $17) 9... c6 $5 10. Bb2 a5 11. a3 Nbd7 12. Nbd2
Ba6 13. Rfe1 Qc7 $11) (7. Nc3 Nc6 {Transposes to the Catalan with Nc3.}) (7.
cxd5 $2 {This is a positional mistake since White's bishop is inactive on g2
and White doesn't even have the minority attack.} exd5 8. Nc3 c6 $15) 7... b6
8. Bb2 Bb7 9. Nc3 $5 {This is probably the best move for White, with the idea
to play Nd2 next.} (9. Nbd2 {This is not a good square for the b1-knight,
except if White can play e4.} Nbd7 $5 (9... a5 $5 10. a3 Nbd7 $11) 10. Rc1 c5
11. cxd5 exd5 $5 $36 (11... Bxd5 $5) 12. dxc5 bxc5 {Black is doing well here.}
13. Nc4 $5 (13. e3 Re8 14. Re1 Bf8 $15 (14... Qb6 15. Qc2 Rad8 16. Qb1 a5 17.
Bc3 Bc6 18. Red1 Bf8 19. Qc2 Ra8 20. Rb1 Qa6 21. Bf1 Qb7 22. Bg2 Qa6 23. Bf1
Qa7 24. Ba1 Qb7 25. Bg2 a4 26. Rdc1 axb3 27. axb3 Qb6 28. b4 c4 29. Nd4 Ba4 30.
Qc3 Ne5 31. Bf1 Bd7 32. N4f3 Nxf3+ 33. Nxf3 Bf5 34. Rb2 Bg4 35. Bg2 Reb8 36. b5
Ra3 37. Qe5 Re8 38. Qd4 Bc5 39. Qd1 Ne4 40. Rbb1 Nxf2 41. Kxf2 Rexe3 42. Bd4
Rxf3+ 43. Bxf3 Bxd4+ 44. Kg2 Bxf3+ 45. Qxf3 Rxf3 46. Kxf3 Bc5 47. Kg2 h5 48.
Rc2 Qg6 49. Rcb2 Qe4+ 50. Kh3 g5 51. b6 g4+ {0-1 Sethuraman,S-Sjugirov,S/chess.
com INT 2021/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 15. Qc2 a5 16. a4 (16. Qb1 a4 $15) 16... Qb6
17. Nb1 Rad8 18. Nc3 Nb8 $1 19. Nb5 Na6 $15 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ga6b4]}) 13...
dxc4 14. Qxd6 Re8 $1 15. e3 cxb3 16. axb3 Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 $132) 9... Nbd7 10.
Nd2 {White wants to play e4, but Black has a very interesting move that
prevents that.} (10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nb5 Be7 {Black can also give up the bishop
on d6 and recapture on d6 with ...cxd6. It would be better if the knight from
d7 was on c6, although the position with the knight on d7 is also playable. In
any case, Black can simply retreat the bishop and then push back the b5-knight.
} 12. Qc2 c6 $132) (10. Rc1 Re8 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb5 Nf8 13. Nxd6 cxd6 $132
14. Ne1 a5 $36 {The bishop from b7 can go to a6 later.} (14... Qe7 15. Bf3 N8h7
$36 (15... Bc8 $5 $36))) 10... Bb4 {A precise move given by the computer,
provoking White to create weaknesses with a3.} 11. a3 (11. Rc1 Qe7 $132) 11...
Be7 $1 {Black wants to play c7-c5 now.} 12. e4 Nxe4 13. Ndxe4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Rb8
$1 {Protecting the bishop on b7, and Black wants to play Nf6 next.} 15. Qc2 Nf6
{In the long run, the weaknesses created on the queenside from the move a3 may
count. For example:} 16. Rad1 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bf6 19. Rfe1 b5 $132
*

