1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 h6 5. Bg2 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Qc2 b6 8. cxd5
exd5 {After the trade on d5, Black's idea is to develop the b8-knight on c6!}
9. Nc3 (9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. b3 Re8 11. Re1 Nc6 (11... Nbd7 12. Bb2 c5 {Playing
with Nbd7 and ...c5 is also possible when White develops the b1-knight to d2.})
12. Bb2 Ne7 {With a standard position for this variation.}) 9... Bb7 10. Nb5 (
10. Bf4 Bxf4 11. gxf4 Nc6 12. Rac1 Ne7 13. Rfd1 Ne8 14. Ne5 Nd6 15. e3 c6 {
The bishop from b7 can be rerouted to f5, Rc8-Rc7 is an idea if it's needed to
prevent any tactics or defend the c6-pawn, and Qe8 with f6 is also an idea, in
order to push the e5-knight back and not allow White to play Ng6.}) 10... Nbd7
{Black should have developed the knight to c6 instead.} (10... Nc6 11. Nxd6
cxd6 {The typical recapture.}) 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. h4 {White was probably afraid
of the move ...g5 at some point and wanted to secure the bishop which will
come to f4.} Re8 (12... a5 {Is also possible.}) 13. Bf4 Ne4 14. Nd2 Ndf6 15.
Nxe4 $6 Nxe4 (15... dxe4 $1 $15 {Black frees the d5-square and creates it as
an outpost for the knight from f6 or the bishop from b7.}) 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17.
Rac1 Rc8 18. Qa4 a6 19. Rxc8 Qxc8 20. Rc1 Qe6 21. Bxd6 e3 22. f3 b5 23. Qa3 Bd5
24. b3 f6 25. Kg2 Rd8 26. Bf4 g5 27. hxg5 hxg5 28. Bc7 Rd7 29. Ba5 Rh7 30. Kg1
Qh3 31. Rc8+ Qxc8 32. Qd6 Qc1+ 0-1

