{This is a very good example of how to play with doubled d-pawns. Black's play
is easier in that pawn structure.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 h6 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2
Bd6 6. Qc2 O-O 7. Nc3 $5 b6 $5 (7... dxc4 $2 {This is a bad move because after:
} 8. e4 {Black can't meet e4 with e6-e5, so White has a good compensation for
the pawn.}) (7... Nc6 {Leads to the Catalan with Nc3.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. O-O Bb7
10. Nb5 Nc6 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Rfe1 Rc8 14. Qa4 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5]}
15. Qa3 Ne4 16. h4 {The idea of this move is to discourage ...g5.} b5 $1 (16...
g5 $5 {Is still playable though.}) (16... Na5 $1 17. b3 Nc6 $3 $15 {This is
the computer's idea, to provoke b3 and after that push the b6-pawn with b5-b4.}
18. Rac1 b5 19. Qb2 b4 (19... Qf6 $15) 20. a3 (20. Bd2 a5 21. Rc2 Qf6 $17)
20... a5 $15) 17. Rac1 Qb6 $1 (17... g5 $5 {Is also possible.}) 18. Red1 (18.
Bxd6 $6 b4 $1 19. Bc5 (19. Rxc6 Bxc6 20. Bxb4 Rb8 $19) 19... Qxc5 $19) 18... b4
(18... a5 $1) (18... Na5 $1 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 19. b3 Nc3 (19... b4 20. Qb2 Nc6 21.
