1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bd6 5. Bg2 h6 6. O-O O-O 7. Nbd2 b6 (7... c5
$1 {This is a good move for Black, although 7...b6 is playable too.}) 8. b3 Bb7
9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Rc1 a5 {This is an interesting idea because if White continues
with 11.a3 as Barp did in the game:} (10... c5 {This move is also possible.}
11. cxd5 exd5 12. dxc5 bxc5 {White gets a chance to activate the d2-knight, so
White should use it.} 13. Nc4 dxc4 14. Qxd6 Re8 $1 15. e3 cxb3 16. axb3 Qb6 17.
Qxb6 axb6 {White has the bishop pair, but the bishop on b7 is very active
which neutralizes the g2-bishop. Black also has a queenside majority and can
aim to create a passed pawn later on.}) 11. a3 (11. cxd5 exd5 12. Qc2 Re8 13.
e3 c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Rfd1 Qb6 {Protecting both bishops against the Nc4
tactic.} 16. Nh4 Bf8 $15 {This is the best move according to the computer,
although usually a very good idea is to wait and provoke the knight to f5, and
only then play Bf8. The point is that the knight is not well placed on the
f5-square.}) 11... Qe7 {This is an annoying move for White to meet, the
a3-pawn is hanging.} 12. a4 Bb4 13. Bc3 c5 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. Qc2 Ne4 16. Nxe4
dxe4 17. Nd2 f5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Rcd1 e5 20. Rfe1 Ne6 21. Nf1 Qc5 22. Ne3 f4
23. Nd5 fxg3 24. hxg3 Qxf2+ 25. Kh2 Rf3 0-1

