{In this chapter, the rare lines in the Queen's Gambit will be analyzed. There
are some interesting and clever sidelines, but in general, they don't have
much theory. For the move orders about entering the Queen's Gambit, against 1.
c4 Black plays 1...e6, and against 1.Nf3, Black can play either 1...d5 or 1...
Nf6.} 1. c4 (1. Nf3 d5 (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 {Black wants to play d5 next.}) 2. c4
e6 {Will be analyzed.}) (1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 (2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 {Leads to the
London system.}) 2... c5 $1 {This is the London system without Nf6. Black
plays 2...c5 immediately and gets a good game.}) 1... e6 {This is the correct
move order after 1.c4 if Black wants to enter the Queen's Gambit.} (1... Nf6 {
Is playable of course, but Black can't get the Queen's Gambit.} 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4
{With a different variation.}) 2. Nc3 (2. Nf3 d5 3. d4 h6 {Transposes to the
Queen's Gambit.}) (2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 {Black doesn't play the move h6 until there
is a threat of Bg5.} Nf6 {And the game is likely to transpose to the proposed
repertoire.}) 2... d5 3. d4 h6 4. e4 $6 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ {Leads to a good
position for Black.} *

