1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 (3... c6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 {Here,
this is a playable move because the ...c6 move is harmful to Black since it
weakens the dark squares.} Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ {This position can be compared
to the note of the sixth move from the main line.}) 4. e4 $6 {This is an
inaccurate move that gives Black at least an equal position.} dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+
{This check is a very strong move, forcing White to play 6.Nc3.} 6. Nc3 {
Black has a choice of two good moves in this position which are 6...c5 and 6...
Nf6.} (6. Bd2 $2 {This move is not working here at all. It's not the same as
the variation starting from 3...c6.} Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ $17 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Bc3
e5 $17 (9... Nf6 $17 {This is also good.})) 6... c5 (6... Nf6 {The move h6 has
been found to be useful on many occasions, preventing the move Bg5.} 7. Nf3 c5
8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 {Black has a good counterplay in the position.}) 7. a3
Bxc3+ (7... Ba5 {This is also possible, but Black will likely need to capture
the knight on c3 sooner or later.}) 8. bxc3 Nf6 9. Nf3 Nc6 (9... Qa5 {This is
the best move for Black.} 10. Bd2 Ne4 {Black wants to capture White's
dark-squared bishop.} 11. Bd3 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 O-O {Two pairs of minor pieces
have been traded, so White doesn't have any attack and there's no compensation
for the damaged pawn structure. Black has a very comfortable position.}) 10.
Be2 O-O 11. O-O Qa5 12. Qb3 Ne4 13. Bb2 Qb6 14. Qc2 Nf6 15. a4 Rd8 16. Rfd1 Bd7
17. Ba3 cxd4 18. cxd4 Be8 19. Bb2 Rac8 20. Bc3 Qc7 21. a5 Qf4 22. Rab1 Rc7 23.
Bd2 Qe4 24. Bd3 Qg4 25. h3 Qh5 26. Bf4 Rcd7 27. Rb5 Nxd4 28. Nxd4 Qxd1+ 29.
Qxd1 Rxd4 30. Rd5 R8xd5 31. cxd5 Rxf4 32. dxe6 fxe6 33. Qb3 Bc6 34. Qxe6+ Kh8
35. a6 Nh5 1-0

