1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e3 a6 $1 6. Bd3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8.
Be2 {This is a bit worse than 8.Bd3 since it doesn't control the center as
much.} Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 (9... c5 10. a3 Nbd7 {Black will postpone cxd4 since
that will open up the bishop from c1. Black will play useful moves instead,
like Bd6, 0-0, and Rc8.} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. b4 Be7 13. Bb2 O-O {In this type of
symmetrical position, neither player should put their knight on c6 or c3 since
the knights are inactive from that square. The knight on d7 will go to b6 and
will have much better prospects from that square.}) 10. b3 (10. a3 c5 11. dxc5
{This is a sample line that discusses the knights on c3 and d7.} Nxc5 (11...
Bxc5 {Is a slightly better move than 11...Nxc5.}) 12. b4 Ncd7 $1 (12... Nce4 $6
{Regardless if the queens are exchanged or not, Black doesn't want to trade
the knight on c3! Instead, Black should retreat with Ncd7, where Black's d7
knight has much better prospects than the knight on c3.} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bb2
$14) 13. Bb2 Be7 {White can hope to equalize at most since the knight on c3 is
misplaced.}) 10... c5 $15 {Black doesn't intend to capture on d4 immediately.
Black will only do that if White plays e3-e4.} 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Rc1 Be7 13. dxc5
Nxc5 14. Ne5 Qb6 15. b4 Ncd7 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. a4 (17. Bf3 {White wants to
activate the c3-knight with Ne4, so Black should prevent that with:} Nf6 {
And it's Black who is fighting for the initiative.} (17... Ne5 $11 {This move
seems to work well tactically and it prevents Ne4, so it's also a good move.}))
17... bxa4 18. Nxa4 Rxc1 19. Qxc1 Qc6 20. Qxc6 Bxc6 21. Nc5 Nxc5 22. bxc5 O-O
23. Bxa6 Ra8 24. Bd3 Bxc5 25. Rc1 Ba3 26. Bxa3 Rxa3 27. Rxc6 Rxd3 28. g4
1/2-1/2

