1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e3 a6 6. cxd5 $2 {This is a big
positional mistake since the bishop on c1 is blocked within the pawn chain.}
exd5 $15 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. Qc2 (8. O-O O-O 9. e4 {It's a now or never moment for
e4 since Black can play Re8 later and it will be more difficult for White to
get e4 in.} dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Nd7 {Black has a very comfortable
position and slightly better chances.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Nc6 {9...Bg4 would
have been met with 10.Ne5, so this move controls the e5-square and threatens
Nb4.} 10. Bf5 $6 (10. a3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3]} 11. Nd2 Re8 {With a good game for
Black.} (11... Qd7 {Is also possible.} 12. b4 {The minority attack is not
threatening when White's bishop is blocked on c1 since that bishop should be
out of the pawn chain or exchanged. Black is not worried on the queenside and
will continue to build up an attack against the White king.})) 10... Bxf5 11.
Qxf5 Re8 {Preventing any e4 ideas that White may have.} 12. Bd2 Ne7 13. Qd3 c6
14. a3 Nc8 {This is an interesting move because the knight may go to b6. Black
doesn't want to put the knight on d6 since that's a square reserved for the
dark-squared bishop until the bishop is not exchanged.} (14... Ng6 $1 15. b4
Ne4 $17 {With the bishop on d6, Black automatically has pressure and a very
good attacking potential on the kingside, so there is no need to worry about
White's minority attack.}) 15. Rfc1 Ne4 16. h3 Bc7 17. Qe2 Nxc3 18. Rxc3 Nd6
19. Rac1 Ne4 20. R3c2 Qd6 21. b4 Ng5 22. Kf1 Re6 23. Nxg5 hxg5 24. g3 Rae8 25.
Kg2 Qd7 26. Qg4 f6 27. a4 Bb8 28. b5 axb5 29. axb5 cxb5 30. Rc5 b6 31. R5c2 Qf7
32. Rc6 Re4 33. Qf5 R8e6 34. Rxe6 Qxe6 35. Rc8+ 1-0

