1. Nf3 d5 (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 (3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 {Transposes to the game.})
3... d5 4. Nc3 {This is another move order that transposes to the game.}) 2. e3
Nf6 {Black does not need to spend a tempo on h6 since White is not threatening
Bg5.} 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 $1 {This is an easy and good solution which avoids
big theoretical lines and is also a good version of the Queen's Gambit
accepted. It's good to note that Black played a6 and captured the pawn on c4
in positions where White's pawn was already on d4. Here, Black starts with 4...
dxc4!} 5. Bxc4 {The bishop from f1 didn't spend one tempo to develop, however,
in the lines when the pawn is on d4, Black had h6 included and White also
recaptured Bxc4 in one move. The downside in White's position is that the
knight has already committed to the c3-square when instead it should have
remained flexible in an ideal scenario.} a6 6. b3 (6. O-O b5 7. Be2 Bb7 8. d4
Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] When White's bishop is on d3, e3-e4 may be an idea, so
Black should strike in the center with ...c5! first. Here, however, the bishop
is on e2 so Black can start with this move.}) (6. d4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {
[%cal Gb8d7] Transposes to the Queen's Gambit accepted, but a very good
version for Black since the knight is misplaced on c3.}) 6... b5 7. Be2 Bb7 8.
Bb2 Nbd7 9. O-O c5 10. a4 b4 11. Nb1 Be7 12. d3 O-O 13. Nbd2 Nd5 14. Rc1 Bf6
15. d4 Rc8 16. Nc4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nc5 18. Bf3 e5 19. Nf5 e4 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21.
Bg4 Nd3 22. Nfd6 Nc3 23. Rxc3 bxc3 24. Bxc8 Bxc8 25. Nxe4 Qg6 26. Nxc3 Bg4 27.
f3 Bh3 28. Qc2 Be6 29. Rd1 Nc5 30. Qxg6 hxg6 31. Na5 Rb8 32. e4 Nxb3 33. Rb1
Rc8 34. Nxb3 Rxc3 35. Nd4 Bc4 36. Rb8+ Kh7 37. Rc8 Rc1+ 38. Kf2 Rf1+ 39. Kg3
Ba2 40. Rc2 Ra1 41. a5 f6 42. h4 Bg8 43. Rc5 Ra4 44. Nc6 Bc4 45. Nd8 Kg8 46.
Nb7 Bf1 47. Rc1 Bb5 48. Rc8+ Kh7 49. Rc2 Ra1 50. Rb2 Bc6 51. Nd8 Bb5 52. Nb7
