1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 {White starts with this move and wants to
play Bb2 and Nc3 next.} dxc4 $1 {Black plays in the same way. The difference
is that White can recapture with the b-pawn, but Black is doing well in that
position too.} 5. bxc4 (5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O b5 7. Be2 Bb7 8. a4 {The good thing
about White's position is that the knight is not on c3, it's on b1 instead.
This means that after b5-b4, White won't need to spend time with the knight.
Regardless, Black also has a good position since Black's pieces will become
active.} b4 9. d4 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 c5 $132) 5... c5 6. Bb2 Nc6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Qc2
b6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. a3 O-O 11. h4 Qd7 12. Rg1 Na5 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. f4 Nd7 15. Nf3
f6 16. h5 a6 17. h6 g6 18. g4 Rae8 19. Nh4 f5 20. Nxf5 exf5 21. gxf5 Bh4+ 22.
Kd1 Bf2 23. Rg5 Bxe3 24. dxe3 Qd6+ 25. Kc1 Rxe3 26. fxg6 Nb3+ 27. Kb1 Nd4 28.
gxh7+ Kh8 29. Nd5 Bxd5 30. Rxd5 Qe6 31. Bd3 Nf6 32. Bxd4 cxd4 33. Rxd4 Qc6 34.
Kb2 Nh5 35. Rg1 Qf6 36. Qc3 Ng3 37. Rg2 b5 38. c5 a5 39. Rd7 Qxc3+ 40. Kxc3
Ne4+ 41. Kc2 Nxc5 42. Rg8+ 1-0

