1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {There are many ways for Black to meet 2.Bf4 and my
recommendation is to play 2...c5 which is objectively best. Note that 2...c5
is against the 2.Bf4 move order since on 2.Nf3, Black plays 2...Nf6. It can be
remembered as the London without Nf6.} c5 3. e3 cxd4 $1 4. exd4 {This is a bad
version for White from the exd5 Caro Kann. In that opening, White would rather
play Bd3 and prevent Bf5 instead of the move Bf4.} Nc6 $1 {Black plays the
London without Nf6! So Black will play Bf5, e6, and then Bd6 with Nge7, or
Nge7 with Ng6. Later on, sometimes f6 can be played if it's needed. This is a
rare system but a very good one for Black.} 5. c3 (5. Nf3 Bf5 6. c3 {Black
plays f6 only when Qb3 and Qd7 are included.} (6. c4 e6 7. Nc3 Bb4 $132) 6...
e6 7. Qb3 Qd7 {Black wants to play f6 now.} 8. Ne5 (8. Nbd2 f6 $15) 8... Nxe5
9. Bxe5 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c6]} 10. Be2 (10. Bb5 Nc6 $15) 10... Nc6 11. Bg3 Be7
12. Nd2 O-O $132 {Black can start a minority attack on the queenside.}) (5. Nc3
Bf5 6. Nb5 $6 Rc8 $15) 5... Bf5 6. Qb3 $6 {This move works well only when
Black's knight is on f6, so in this position, it doesn't work at all.} Qd7 7.
Nf3 $6 f6 $1 {Black plays f6 only when White's queen is on b3. White needs to
know the move 8.h4 in order to be just slightly worse, however, it's likely
that if White knew the theory, Qb3 wouldn't have been played.} 8. Nbd2 e6 {
This move is inaccurate since it gives White another chance to play the move 9.
h4.} (8... g5 $1 $15 9. Bg3 {Black is positionally better not just because the
bishop on g3 will be under attack and Black will gain some tempi, but also
because of the White knights, both of them are badly placed.} (9. Be3 e6 $15)
9... e6 10. Be2 h5 11. h4 g4 12. Nh2 Bg6 $1 {The best move according to the
computer: Black's idea is to bring the g8-knight to the f5-square.} (12... Nge7
13. O-O Bg6 $17 (13... Bh6 $17)) 13. O-O Bh6 $1 14. Qd1 (14. f4 Nge7 $19) 14...
f5 $3 {An amazing strategical move! Blocking the bishop on g6 but threatening
f5-f4. White's knights are powerless to help prevent f4.} 15. f4 (15. Be5 Nxe5
16. dxe5 Bf4 $19 (16... O-O-O $19)) 15... Nf6 $17 (15... Qd6 $17)) 9. Be2 $2 (
9. h4 $1 Nh6 $1 $36 {Intending Nf7.} 10. Bxh6 $6 gxh6 $15 {Black is better
because of the bishop pair and White's h-pawn since it's on h4 instead of h2,
which created additional weaknesses for White.}) (9. Nh4 $2 g5 $1 {White loses
a piece.} 10. Nxf5 exf5 11. Be3 f4 $19) 9... g5 10. Bg3 h5 11. h4 g4 12. Nh2
Nge7 $1 (12... Bg6 $1 $17) (12... Bh6 $1 $17) 13. Nhf1 Bh6 14. Qa3 O-O $1 15.
Qd6 (15. Ne3 Bg6 $19 (15... e5 $17)) 15... Qe8 $19 16. Qc7 e5 17. dxe5 fxe5 18.
Ne3 Be6 19. Qd6 Qg6 20. Qa3 Rad8 $19 (20... d4 $19) 21. O-O d4 22. cxd4 exd4
23. Nec4 d3 24. Bd1 Nf5 25. Re1 Nxg3 26. fxg3 Nd4 27. Ne3 Qf6 28. Kh2 Qf2 29.
Bb3 Nxb3 30. Ne4 Qf7 31. axb3 d2 32. Rf1 Qg6 33. Rxf8+ Rxf8 34. Ng5 Bxg5 35.
hxg5 Qxg5 36. Nf1 Qd8 37. Ne3 Qd4 38. Qxa7 Qxa7 39. Rxa7 Rd8 40. Rxb7 d1=Q 41.
Nxd1 Rxd1 42. Re7 Bd5 43. Re2 Kf7 44. Rf2+ Kg6 45. b4 Rd3 46. Re2 Kf5 47. b5
Be4 48. b6 Rb3 49. Rf2+ Ke5 50. Re2 Rxb6 51. Kg1 Rb3 52. Kh2 Rd3 53. Rc2 h4 0-1

