1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 {Transposes to the Queen's Gambit.}) 2...
Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 $1 {5...e6 is also possible but there is
more theory on it. Getting the bishop out of the pawn chain and only then
playing e6 is much simpler.} (5... cxd4 $1 6. exd4 Bg4 $5 {is also simple and
good}) 6. c3 e6 7. Qa4 {White may have some ideas to jump Ne5, so Black's next
move breaks the pin and makes White's Ne5 harmless.} Nd7 8. Bb5 Qc8 $11 9. h3
Bh5 10. O-O {White has some pressure in the position, but it's only temporary.}
a6 11. Bd3 b5 12. Qd1 Be7 13. Qb1 Bg6 14. e4 cxd4 15. exd5 exd5 16. cxd4 O-O
